item.title: Labor elders set to fix Victorian branch
item.description: Labor's national executive is to step in to clean up the Victorian branch, taking over preselections and appointing two administrators.

item.title: ‘Sex-motivation’ for all Claremont crimes
item.description: Bradley Robert Edwards escalated from sexual assaults to serial killings and may have claimed an earlier murder victim had his violent rape of a teenager not been interrupted, a court has heard.

item.title: Asian shares higher as virus fears ease
item.description: Asian shares have rallied, bolstered by the formal start of the Federal Reserve's corporate bond buying program, and as earlier worries about a second wave of coronavirus infections ease.

item.title: More tickets to ride coming up in NSW
item.description: It's still not "all aboard", but NSW's public transport passenger levels are slowly overcoming coronavirus constraints.

item.title: Testing economic time for NSW: treasurer
item.description: NSW's unemployment rate is forecast to reach 7.75 per cent, with 275,000 people losing their jobs as the state grapples with the financial fallout of drought, bushfires and the coronavirus pandemic.

item.title: Multiple firestorms during 2019-20 blazes
item.description: Australia experienced almost as many firestorms - bushfires so intense they create their own weather systems - during the 'Black Summer' season as in the previous three decades.

item.title: UK funds human trials of virus vaccine
item.description: Scientists at Imperial College London will start the first clinical trials of a potential COVID-19 vaccine this week with more than 45 million pounds ($A81.9 million) in backing from the British government and philanthropic donors.

item.title: Court bid to stop export of WA sheep fails
item.description: About 35,000 sheep will be sent from Western Australia to the Middle East during the northern summer after Animals Australia lost a Federal Court challenge to stop the live export.

item.title: JobKeeper jobs won’t all be kept: minister
item.description: The Morrison government has conceded some workers now getting wage subsidies will be pushed into unemployment when the JobKeeper scheme ends.

item.title: Qld public sector pay rise pushed to 2022
item.description: Queensland public servants who were due for a pay rise in the next financial year will now have to wait until 2022.
